 the United States arose out of slavery and blackface. Blacksound as an idea is not the music or sounds produced by Black Americans but instead the material and fleeting remnants of their sounds and performances that have been co-opted and amalgamated into popular music. Morrison unpacks the relationship between performance, racial identity, and intellectual property to reveal how blackface minstrelsy scripts became absorbed into commercial entertainment through an unequal system of intellectual property and copyright laws. By introducing this foundational new concept in musicology, Blacksound highlights what is politically at stake—for creators and audiences alike—in revisiting the long history of American popular music.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican American musiciansxRace identityzUnited States. 0aAfrican American musiciansxSocial conditions. 0aMinstrel musiczUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aMinstrel showszUnited States. 0aPopular musiczUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079135840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520390607?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520390607423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520390607/original  a978-3-11-079135-8  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles